properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall amounts of 20 to 35 mm are expected today and tonight. Rain will continue to spread eastward this morning and will continue into tonight. Total rainfall amounts of 20 to 35 mm are forecast by Thursday morning. Locally higher amounts are possible. The ground has limited ability to absorb further rainfall. Flood messaging is in effect for much of Central and Eastern Ontario. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local Conservation Authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry District Office. This rainfall is associated with a Texas Low that will track across Southern Ontario today. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, snow or freezing precipitation on Wednesday... A low pressure system will track across the Great Lakes today, bringing a mixture of precipitation across the Outaouais. Precipitation will mostly begin as rain midday before changing to snow over areas further to the north this afternoon. The snow may change over to freezing rain Thursday evening or overnight. Rainfall amounts could approach 25 millimetres along the Ottawa River while areas further north could see 5 centimetres of wet, heavy snow. Significant ice accretion is also possible before precipitation comes to an end Thursday morning. Possibly heavy rain could contribute to rising water levels. The wet, heavy snow and freezing precipitation could cause driving conditions to deteriorate and put significant weight on trees and power lines. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A messy mix of snow and ice pellets beginning this morning changing to rain or freezing rain this afternoon. Precipitation will begin as snow and ice pellets this morning. Snow and ice pellet amounts of 2 to 5 cm are possible before the precipitation changes to rain this afternoon. However, with temperatures expected to remain near the zero degree mark there is the risk of freezing rain this afternoon. There is also uncertainty as to how much precipitation will fall as rain or freezing rain. Current indications are that rainfall amounts of 15 to 25 mm are possible by Thursday morning. For information concerning flooding, please consult your local Conservation Authority or Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources and Forestry District Office. This precipitation is associated with a Texas Low that will track across Southern Ontario today. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and freezing rain likely Wednesday evening... A low pressure system will track across the Great Lakes today, bringing a mixture of precipitation across the Laurentians. Precipitation will begin as snow late in the afternoon or early in the evening before changing to freezing rain or rain near midnight. About 5 centimetres of wet, heavy snow is expected locally this evening, especially over higher terrain. Significant ice accretion is also possible in some areas before precipitation comes to an end Thursday morning. Travel may be difficult due to snow and freezing precipitation. The weight of the wet, heavy snow and the ice may impact trees and power lines. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected this afternoon and evening. Precipitation will begin as snow and ice pellets this morning. Snow and ice pellet amounts of 2 to 5 cm are possible before the precipitation changes to freezing rain this afternoon. Freezing rain will last for several hours before changing to rain tonight. This wintry precipitation is associated with a Texas Low that will track across Southern Ontario later today and tonight. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Substantial high-elevation snowfall continues. Roughly 5 cm of snow is expected along the west coast today into tonight. Accumulations may reach as high as 25 cm along the highest parts of the Viking Trail between Wiltondale and Bonne Bay. Similar or higher totals are likely across higher parts of the Long Range Mountains. The snow will begin to ease tonight. Back-country trails or high-elevation roads will continue to be difficult to navigate due to the accumulating snow. ### Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard this morning at Hall Beach. Falling snow and winds gusting to 80 km/h are creating blizzard conditions at Hall Beach this morning. Visibilities will improve as winds gradually begin to diminish late this morning or this afternoon. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
